<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="420" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,870,1184]" pageId="5" pageNumber="420">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,324,942,968]" pageId="5" pageNumber="420">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Wileman" baseAuthorityYear="1911" box="[332,462,942,968]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Termioptycha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="420" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bilineata">
<emphasis box="[332,462,942,968]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="420">T. bilineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is diagnosed by the central Y mark of forewing densely covered with fuscous brown scales. In male genitalia, pair of apical spine like process on an approximately rectangular uncus and a conspicuously long ampulla are diagnostic. Morphologically, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Wileman" baseAuthorityYear="1911" box="[747,875,1014,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Termioptycha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="420" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bilineata">
<emphasis box="[747,875,1014,1040]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="420">T. bilineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Butler" authorityYear="1879" box="[1111,1223,1015,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Locastra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="420" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inimica">
<emphasis box="[1111,1223,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="420">T. inimica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Rong, H. &amp; Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H." box="[1238,1432,1014,1041]" pageId="5" pageNumber="420" pagination="159 - 174" refId="ref5769" refString="Rong, H., Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H. (2017) Review of the genus Termioptycha Meyrick, 1889 (Lepidoptera, Pyralidae) from China, with descriptions of four new species. Zootaxa, 4329 (2), 159 - 174. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4329.2.3" type="journal article" year="2017">
Rong 
<emphasis box="[1308,1358,1014,1040]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="420">et al</emphasis>
. 2017
</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 13) but can be easily separated on the basis of male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1340,1086,1113]" pageId="5" pageNumber="420" type="distribution">
